#: src/3537-msrv-resolver.md:188
msgid "People have tried to reduce the pain from MSRV with its own costs:"
msgstr ""

#: src/3537-msrv-resolver.md:189
msgid "Treating it as a breaking change:"
msgstr ""

#: src/3537-msrv-resolver.md:190
msgid ""
"This leads to extra churn in the ecosystem when a fraction of users are "
"likely going to benefit"
msgstr ""

#: src/3537-msrv-resolver.md:191
msgid ""
"We have the precedence elsewhere in the Rust ecosystem for build and runtime "
"system requirement changes not being breaking, like when rustc requires "
"newer versions of glibc, Android NDK, etc."
msgstr ""

#: src/3537-msrv-resolver.md:192
msgid "Adding upper limits to version requirements:"
msgstr ""

#: src/3537-msrv-resolver.md:193
msgid ""
"This fractures the ecosystem by making packages incompatible with each other "
"and the Cargo team [discourages doing this](https://doc.rust-lang.org/cargo/"
"reference/specifying-dependencies.html#multiple-requirements)"
msgstr ""

#: src/3537-msrv-resolver.md:194
msgid ""
"Avoiding dependencies, re-implementing it themselves at the cost of their "
"time and the risk for bugs, especially if `unsafe` is involved"
msgstr ""

#: src/3537-msrv-resolver.md:195
msgid "Ensuring dependencies have a more inclusive MSRV policy then themselves"
msgstr ""

#: src/3537-msrv-resolver.md:196
msgid ""
"This has lead to long arguments in the ecosystem over what is the right "
"policy for updating a minimum-supported Rust version (MSRV), wearing on all "
"(e.g. [libc](https://github.com/rust-lang/libs-team/issues/72), [time]"
"(https://github.com/time-rs/time/discussions/535) )"
msgstr ""

#: src/3537-msrv-resolver.md:204
msgid ""
"The sooner we improve the status quo, the better, as it can take years for "
"these changes to percolate out to those exclusively developing with an older "
"Rust version (in contrast with the example above). This delay can be reduced "
"somewhat if a newer toolchain can be used for development version without "
"upgrading the MSRV."
msgstr ""

#: src/3537-msrv-resolver.md:210
msgid "Workflows"
msgstr ""

#: src/3537-msrv-resolver.md:212
msgid ""
"In solving this, we need to keep in mind how people are using Cargo and how "
"to prioritize when needs of different workflows conflict. We will then look "
"at the potential designs within the context of this framework."
msgstr ""

#: src/3537-msrv-resolver.md:215
msgid "Some design criteria we can use for evaluating workflows:"
msgstr ""

#: src/3537-msrv-resolver.md:216
msgid "Cargo should not make major breaking changes"
msgstr ""

#: src/3537-msrv-resolver.md:217
msgid "Low barrier to entry"
msgstr ""

#: src/3537-msrv-resolver.md:218
msgid ""
"The costs of “non-recommended” setups should focused on those that need them"
msgstr ""

#: src/3537-msrv-resolver.md:219
msgid "Encourage a standard of quality within the ecosystem, including"
msgstr ""

#: src/3537-msrv-resolver.md:220
msgid ""
"Assumption that things will work as advertised (e.g. our success with MSRV)"
msgstr ""

#: src/3537-msrv-resolver.md:221
msgid "A pleasant experience (e.g. meaningful error messages)"
msgstr ""

#: src/3537-msrv-resolver.md:222
msgid "Secure"
msgstr ""

#: src/3537-msrv-resolver.md:223
msgid ""
"Every feature has a cost and we should balance the cost against the value we "
"expect"
msgstr ""

#: src/3537-msrv-resolver.md:224
msgid ""
"Features can further constrain what can be done in the future due to "
"backwards compatibility"
msgstr ""

#: src/3537-msrv-resolver.md:225
msgid "Features increase maintenance burden"
msgstr ""

#: src/3537-msrv-resolver.md:226
msgid ""
"The larger the user-facing surface, the less likely users will find the "
"feature they need and instead use the quickest shortcut"
msgstr ""

#: src/3537-msrv-resolver.md:227
msgid ""
"Being transparent makes debugging easier, helps in evaluating risks "
"(including security), and builds confidence in users"
msgstr ""

#: src/3537-msrv-resolver.md:228
msgid "Encourage progress and avoid stagnation"
msgstr ""

#: src/3537-msrv-resolver.md:229
msgid ""
"Proactively upgrading means the total benefit to developers from investments "
"made in Rust is higher"
msgstr ""

#: src/3537-msrv-resolver.md:230
msgid ""
"Conversely, when most of the community is on old versions, it has a chilling "
"effect on improving Rust"
msgstr ""

#: src/3537-msrv-resolver.md:231
msgid ""
"This also means feedback can come more quickly, making it easier and cheaper "
"to pivot with user needs"
msgstr ""

#: src/3537-msrv-resolver.md:232
msgid ""
"Spreading the cost of upgrades over time makes forced-upgrades (e.g. for a "
"security vulnerability) less of an emergency"
msgstr ""

#: src/3537-msrv-resolver.md:233
msgid "Our commitment to compatibility helps keep the cost of upgrade low"
msgstr ""

#: src/3537-msrv-resolver.md:234
msgid ""
"When not competing with the above, we should do the right thing for the user "
"rather than disrupt their flow to tell them what they should instead do"
msgstr ""

#: src/3537-msrv-resolver.md:236
msgid "And keeping in mind"
msgstr ""

#: src/3537-msrv-resolver.md:237
msgid ""
"The Rust project only supports the latest version (e.g bug and security "
"fixes) and the burden for support for older versions is on the vendor "
"providing the older Rust toolchain."
msgstr ""

#: src/3537-msrv-resolver.md:240
msgid ""
"Even keeping upgrade costs low, there is still a re-validation cost that "
"mission critical applications must pay"
msgstr ""

#: src/3537-msrv-resolver.md:241
msgid ""
"Dependencies in `Cargo.lock` are not expected to change from contributors "
"using different versions of the Rust toolchain without an explicit action "
"like changing `Cargo.toml` or running `cargo update`"
msgstr ""

#: src/3537-msrv-resolver.md:242
msgid ""
"e.g. If the maintainer does `cargo add foo && git commit && git push`, then "
"a contributor doing `git pull && cargo check` should not have a different "
"selection of dependencies, independent of their toolchain versions (which "
"might mean the second user sees an error about an incompatible package)."
msgstr ""

#: src/3537-msrv-resolver.md:245
msgid "Some implications:"
msgstr ""

#: src/3537-msrv-resolver.md:246
msgid ""
"\"Support\" in MSRV implies the same quality and responsiveness to bug "
"reports, regardless of Rust version"
msgstr ""

#: src/3537-msrv-resolver.md:247
msgid ""
"MSRV applies to all interactions with a project within the maintainers "
"control (including as a registry dependency, `cargo install --locked`, as a "
"git dependency, contributor experience; excluding transitive dependencies, "
"rust-analyzer, etc), unless documented otherwise like"
msgstr ""

#: src/3537-msrv-resolver.md:250
msgid ""
"Some projects may document that enabling a feature will affect the MSRV (e."
"g. [moka](https://docs.rs/moka/0.12.1/moka/#minimum-supported-rust-versions))"
msgstr ""

#: src/3537-msrv-resolver.md:251
msgid ""
"Some projects may have a higher MSRV for building the repo (e.g. `Cargo."
"lock` with newer dependencies, reliance on cargo features that get stripped "
"on publish)"
msgstr ""

#: src/3537-msrv-resolver.md:252
msgid ""
"We should focus the cost for maintaining support for older versions of Rust "
"on the user of the old version and away from the maintainer or the other "
"users of the library or tool"
msgstr ""

#: src/3537-msrv-resolver.md:253
msgid ""
"Costs include lower developer productivity due to lack of access to "
"features, APIs that don't integrate with the latest features, and slower "
"build times due to pulling in extra code to make up for missing features (e."
"g. clap dropping its dependency on [is-terminal](https://crates.io/crates/is-"
"terminal) in favor of [`IsTerminal`](https://doc.rust-lang.org/std/io/trait."
"IsTerminal.html) cut build time from [6s to 3s](https://github.com/rosetta-"
"rs/argparse-rosetta-rs/commit/378cd2c30679afdf9b9843dbadea3e8951090809))"
msgstr ""

#: src/3537-msrv-resolver.md:261 src/3537-msrv-resolver.md:1055
#: src/3537-msrv-resolver.md:1086 src/3537-msrv-resolver.md:1117
#: src/3537-msrv-resolver.md:1149
msgid "Latest Rust with no MSRV"
msgstr ""

#: src/3537-msrv-resolver.md:263
msgid "A user runs `cargo new` and starts development."
msgstr ""

#: src/3537-msrv-resolver.md:265
msgid ""
"A maintainer may also want to avoid constraining their dependents, for a "
"variety of reasons, and leave MSRV support as a gray area."
msgstr ""

#: src/3537-msrv-resolver.md:267
msgid "**Priority 1 because:**"
msgstr ""

#: src/3537-msrv-resolver.md:268
msgid ""
"✅ No MSRV is fine as pushing people to have an MSRV would lead to either"
msgstr ""

#: src/3537-msrv-resolver.md:269
msgid ""
"an inaccurate reported MSRV from it going stale which would lower the "
"quality of the ecosystem"
msgstr ""

#: src/3537-msrv-resolver.md:270
msgid ""
"raise the barrier to entry by requiring more process for packages and "
"pushing the cost of old Rust versions on people who don't care"
msgstr ""

#: src/3537-msrv-resolver.md:272 src/3537-msrv-resolver.md:343
#: src/3537-msrv-resolver.md:374
msgid "**Pain points:**"
msgstr ""

#: src/3537-msrv-resolver.md:274
msgid ""
"The Rust toolchain does not provide a way to help users know new dependency "
"versions are available, to support the users in staying up-to-date. MSRV "
"build errors from new dependency versions is one way to do it though not "
"ideal as this disrupts the user. Otherwise, they must actively run `rustup "
"update` or follow Rust news."
msgstr ""

#: src/3537-msrv-resolver.md:278
msgid ""
"For dependents, this makes it harder to know what versions are \"safe\" to "
"use."
msgstr ""

#: src/3537-msrv-resolver.md:280 src/3537-msrv-resolver.md:1058
#: src/3537-msrv-resolver.md:1089 src/3537-msrv-resolver.md:1120
#: src/3537-msrv-resolver.md:1152
msgid "Latest Rust as the MSRV"
msgstr ""

#: src/3537-msrv-resolver.md:282
msgid ""
"A maintainer regularly updates their MSRV to latest. They can choose to "
"provide a level of support for old MSRVs by reserving MSRV changes to minor "
"version bumps, giving them room to backport fixes. Due to the pain points "
"listed below, the target audience for this workflow is likely small, likely "
"pushing them to not specify their MSRV."
msgstr ""

#: src/3537-msrv-resolver.md:289
msgid "**Priority 2 because:**"
msgstr ""

#: src/3537-msrv-resolver.md:290
msgid "✅ Low barrier to maintaining a high quality of support for their MSRV"
msgstr ""

#: src/3537-msrv-resolver.md:291
msgid ""
"✅ Being willing to advertising an MSRV, even if latest, improves the "
"information available to developers, increasing the quality of the ecosystem"
msgstr ""

#: src/3537-msrv-resolver.md:292
msgid ""
"✅ Costs for dealing with old Rust toolchains is shifted from the maintainer "
"and the users on a supported toolchain to those on an unsupported toolchain"
msgstr ""

#: src/3537-msrv-resolver.md:293
msgid ""
"✅ By focusing new development on latest MSRV, this provides a carrot to "
"encourage others to actively upgrading"
msgstr ""

#: src/3537-msrv-resolver.md:295
msgid "**Pain points (in addition to the prior workflow):**"
msgstr ""

#: src/3537-msrv-resolver.md:297
msgid ""
"In addition to their toolchain version, the Rust toolchain does not help "
"these users with keeping their MSRV up-to-date. They can use other tools "
"like [RenovateBot](https://github.com/rust-lang/cargo/"
"blob/87eb374d499100bc945dc0e50ae5194ae539b964/.github/renovate.json5#L12-"
"L24) though that causes extra churn in the repo."
msgstr ""

#: src/3537-msrv-resolver.md:303
msgid ""
"A package could offer a lower MSRV in an unofficial capacity or with a lower "
"quality of support but the requirement that dependents always pass `--ignore-"
"rust-version` makes this disruptive."
msgstr ""

#: src/3537-msrv-resolver.md:306 src/3537-msrv-resolver.md:1063
#: src/3537-msrv-resolver.md:1095 src/3537-msrv-resolver.md:1126
#: src/3537-msrv-resolver.md:1157
msgid "Extended MSRV"
msgstr ""

#: src/3537-msrv-resolver.md:308
msgid ""
"This could be people exclusively running one version or that support a range "
"of versions. So why are people on old versions?"
msgstr ""

#: src/3537-msrv-resolver.md:310
msgid ""
"Not everyone is focused on Rust development and might only touch their Rust "
"code once every couple of months, making it a pain if they have to update "
"every time."
msgstr ""

#: src/3537-msrv-resolver.md:312
msgid ""
"Think back to slow git index updates when you've stepped away and consider "
"people who we'd be telling to run `rustup update` every time they touch Rust"
msgstr ""

#: src/3537-msrv-resolver.md:313
msgid ""
"While a distribution provides rust to build other packages in the "
"distribution, users might assume that is a version to use, rather than "
"getting Rust through `rustup`"
msgstr ""

#: src/3537-msrv-resolver.md:315
msgid ""
"Re-validation costs for updating core parts of the image for an embedded "
"Linux developers can be high, keeping them on older versions"
msgstr ""

#: src/3537-msrv-resolver.md:316
msgid ""
"Updates can be slow within tightly controlled environments (airgaps, "
"paperwork, etc)"
msgstr ""

#: src/3537-msrv-resolver.md:317
msgid ""
"Qualifying Rust toolchains takes time and money, see [Ferrocene](https://"
"ferrous-systems.com/ferrocene/)"
msgstr ""

#: src/3537-msrv-resolver.md:318
msgid ""
"Built on or for systems that are no longer supported by rustc (e.g. old "
"glibc, AndroidNDK, etc)"
msgstr ""

#: src/3537-msrv-resolver.md:319
msgid "Library and tool maintainers catering to the above use cases"
msgstr ""

#: src/3537-msrv-resolver.md:321
msgid ""
"The MSRV may extend back only a couple releases or to a year+ and they may "
"choose to update on an as-need basis or keep to a strict cadence."
msgstr ""

#: src/3537-msrv-resolver.md:324
msgid ""
"Depending on the reason they are working with an old version, they might be "
"developing the project with it or they might be using the latest toolchain. "
"For some of these use cases, they might controlling their \"MSRV\" via `rust-"
"toolchain.toml`, rather than `package.rust-version`, as its their only "
"supported Rust version (e.g. an application with a vetted toolchain)."
msgstr ""

#: src/3537-msrv-resolver.md:328
msgid ""
"When multiple Rust versions are supported, like with library and tool "
"maintainers, they will need to verify at least their MSRV and latest. "
"Ideally, they also [verify their latest dependencies](https://doc.rust-lang."
"org/cargo/guide/continuous-integration.html#verifying-latest-dependencies) "
"though this is already a recommended practice when people follow the "
"[default choice to commit their lockfile](https://doc.rust-lang.org/cargo/"
"faq.html#why-have-cargolock-in-version-control). The way they verify "
"dependencies is restricted as they can't rely on always updating via "
"Dependabot/RenovateBot as a way to verify them. Maintainers likely only need "
"to do a compilation check for MSRV as their regular CI runs ensure that the "
"behavior (which is usually independent of rust version) is correct for the "
"MSRV-compatible dependencies."
msgstr ""

#: src/3537-msrv-resolver.md:336
msgid "**Priority 3 because:**"
msgstr ""

#: src/3537-msrv-resolver.md:337
msgid "✅ Several use cases for this workflow have little alternative"
msgstr ""

#: src/3537-msrv-resolver.md:338
msgid ""
"✅ MSRV applies to all interactions to the project which also means that the "
"level of \"support\" is consistent"
msgstr ""

#: src/3537-msrv-resolver.md:339
msgid ""
"❌ This implies stagnation and there are cases where people could more "
"easily use newer toolchains, like Debian users, but that is less so the case "
"for other users"
msgstr ""

#: src/3537-msrv-resolver.md:340
msgid ""
"❌ For library and tool maintainers, they are absorbing costs from these "
"less common use cases"
msgstr ""

#: src/3537-msrv-resolver.md:341 src/3537-msrv-resolver.md:372
msgid ""
"They could shift these costs to those that need old versions by switching to "
"the \"Latest MSRV\" workflow by allowing their users to backport fixes to "
"prior MSRV releases"
msgstr ""

#: src/3537-msrv-resolver.md:345
msgid ""
"Maintaining a working `Cargo.lock` is frustrating, as demonstrated earlier."
msgstr ""

#: src/3537-msrv-resolver.md:347
msgid ""
