"The MSRV-compatibility build check will be demoted from an error to a "
"`deny`\\-by-default workspace [diagnostic](https://github.com/rust-lang/"
"cargo/issues/12235), allowing users to intentionally use dependencies on an "
"unsupported (or less supported) version of Rust without requiring `--ignore-"
"rust-version` on every invocation."
msgstr ""

#: src/3537-msrv-resolver.md:850
msgid ""
"Ideally, we present all of the MSRV issues upfront to be resolved together. "
"At minimum, we should present a top-down message, rather than bottom up."
msgstr ""

#: src/3537-msrv-resolver.md:853
msgid ""
"If `package.rust-version` is unset or `\"tbd-name-representing-currently-"
"running-rust-toolchain\"`, the diagnostic should suggest setting it to help "
"raise awareness of `package.rust-version` being able to reduce future "
"resolution errors. This would benefit from knowing the oldest MSRV."
msgstr ""

#: src/3537-msrv-resolver.md:858
msgid "`cargo update`"
msgstr ""

#: src/3537-msrv-resolver.md:860
msgid ""
"`cargo update` will inform users when an MSRV or semver incompatible version "
"is available. `cargo update --dry-run` will also report this information so "
"that users can check on the status of this at any time."
msgstr ""

#: src/3537-msrv-resolver.md:863 src/3537-msrv-resolver.md:903
msgid "Users may pass"
msgstr ""

#: src/3537-msrv-resolver.md:864 src/3537-msrv-resolver.md:904
msgid ""
"`--ignore-rust-version` to pick the latest dependencies, ignoring all `rust-"
"version` fields (your own and from dependencies)"
msgstr ""

#: src/3537-msrv-resolver.md:865 src/3537-msrv-resolver.md:905
msgid ""
"`--update-rust-version` to pick the `rustc --version`\\-compatible "
"dependencies, updating your `package.rust-version` if needed to match the "
"highest of your dependencies"
msgstr ""

#: src/3537-msrv-resolver.md:866
msgid ""
"`<pkgname> --precise <version>` to pick a specific version, independent of "
"the `rust-version` field"
msgstr ""

#: src/3537-msrv-resolver.md:868
msgid ""
"We expect the notice to inform users of these options for allowing them to "
"upgrade."
msgstr ""

#: src/3537-msrv-resolver.md:870
msgid "Those flags will also be added to `cargo generate-lockfile`"
msgstr ""

#: src/3537-msrv-resolver.md:872
msgid "Syncing `Cargo.toml` to `Cargo.lock` on any Cargo command"
msgstr ""

#: src/3537-msrv-resolver.md:874
msgid ""
"In addition to the `cargo update` output to report when things are held back "
"(both MSRV and semver), we will try having dependency resolves highlight "
"newly selected dependency versions that were held back due to MSRV or "
"semver. Whether we do this and how much will be subject to factors like "
"noisy output, performance, etc."
msgstr ""

#: src/3537-msrv-resolver.md:878
msgid "Some approaches we can take for doing this include:"
msgstr ""

#: src/3537-msrv-resolver.md:880
msgid ""
"After resolving, we can do a depth-first diff of the trees, stopping and "
"reporting on the first different node. This would let us report on any "
"command that changes the way the tree is resolved (from explicit changes "
"with `cargo update` to `cargo build` syncing `Cargo.toml` changes to `Cargo."
"lock`). We'd likely want to limit the output to only the sub-tree that "
"changed. If there wasn't previously a `Cargo.lock`, this would mean "
"everything."
msgstr ""

#: src/3537-msrv-resolver.md:886
msgid ""
"We could either always do the second resolve or only do the second resolve "
"if the resolver changed anything, whichever is faster."
msgstr ""

#: src/3537-msrv-resolver.md:889
msgid ""
"Its unknown whether making the inputs available for multiple resolves would "
"have a performance impact."
msgstr ""

#: src/3537-msrv-resolver.md:891
msgid ""
"While a no-change resolve is fast, if this negatively impacts it enough, we "
"could explore hashing the resolve inputs and storing that in the lockfile, "
"allowing us to detect if the inputs have changed and only resolving then."
msgstr ""

#: src/3537-msrv-resolver.md:896
msgid "`cargo add`"
msgstr ""

#: src/3537-msrv-resolver.md:898
msgid ""
"`cargo add <pkg>` (no version) will pick a version requirement that is low "
"enough so that when it resolves, it can pick a dependency that is MSRV-"
"compatible. `cargo add` will warn when it does this."
msgstr ""

#: src/3537-msrv-resolver.md:907
msgid "`cargo publish`"
msgstr ""

#: src/3537-msrv-resolver.md:909
msgid ""
"`package.rust-version` will gain support for an `\"tbd-name-representing-"
"currently-running-rust-toolchain\"` value, in addition to partial versions. "
"On `cargo publish` / `cargo package`, the generated `*.crate`s `Cargo.toml` "
"will have `\"tbd-name-representing-currently-running-rust-toolchain\"` "
"replaced with `rustc --version`. If `rustc --version` is a pre-release, "
"publish will fail."
msgstr ""

#: src/3537-msrv-resolver.md:913
msgid ""
"`cargo new` will include `package.rust-version = \"tbd-name-representing-"
"currently-running-rust-toolchain\"`."
msgstr ""

#: src/3537-msrv-resolver.md:915
msgid "Drawbacks"
msgstr ""

#: src/3537-msrv-resolver.md:918
msgid ""
"Users upgrading to the next Edition (or changing to `resolver = '3\"`), will "
"have to manually update their CI to test the latest dependencies with "
"`CARGO_RESOLVER_PRECEDENCE=maximum`."
msgstr ""

#: src/3537-msrv-resolver.md:920
msgid ""
"Workspaces have no `edition`, so its easy for users to not realize they need "
"to set `resolver = \"3\"` or to update their `resolver = \"2\"` to `\"3\"` "
"(Cargo only warns on [virtual manifests without an explicit `workspace."
"resolver`](https://github.com/rust-lang/cargo/pull/10910))."
msgstr ""

#: src/3537-msrv-resolver.md:923
msgid ""
"While we hope this will give maintainers more freedom to upgrade their MSRV, "
"this could instead further entrench rust-version stagnation in the ecosystem."
msgstr ""

#: src/3537-msrv-resolver.md:926
msgid ""
"For projects with larger MSRVs than their dependencies, this introduces "
"another form of drift from the latest dependencies (in addition to "
"[lockfiles](https://doc.rust-lang.org/cargo/faq.html#why-have-cargolock-in-"
"version-control)). However, we already recommend people [verify their latest "
"dependencies](https://doc.rust-lang.org/nightly/cargo/guide/continuous-"
"integration.html#verifying-latest-dependencies), so the only scenario this "
"further degrades is when lockfiles are verified by always updating to the "
"latest, like with RenovateBot, and only in the sense that the user needs to "
"know to explicitly take action to add another verification job to CI."
msgstr ""

#: src/3537-msrv-resolver.md:934
msgid "Rationale and alternatives"
msgstr ""

#: src/3537-msrv-resolver.md:937
msgid "Misc alternatives"
msgstr ""

#: src/3537-msrv-resolver.md:938
msgid ""
"Dependencies with unspecified `package.rust-version`: we could mark these as "
"always-compatible or always-incompatible; there really isn't a right answer "
"here."
msgstr ""

#: src/3537-msrv-resolver.md:939
msgid ""
"The resolver doesn't support backtracking as that is extra complexity that "
"we can always adopt later as we've reserved the right to make adjustments to "
"what `cargo generate-lockfile` will produce over time."
msgstr ""

#: src/3537-msrv-resolver.md:940
msgid ""
"`CARGO_RESOLVER_PRECEDENCE` is used, rather than a CLI option (e.g. ensuring "
"every command has `--ignore-rust-version` or a `--rust-version <x.y.z>`)"
msgstr ""

#: src/3537-msrv-resolver.md:941
msgid ""
"This is unlikely to be used in one-off cases but across whole interactions "
"which is better suited for config / env variables, rather than CLI options"
msgstr ""

#: src/3537-msrv-resolver.md:942
msgid "Minimize CLI clutter"
msgstr ""

#: src/3537-msrv-resolver.md:943
msgid ""
"`CARGO_RESOLVER_PRECEDENCE=rust-version` implies maximal resolution among "
"MSRV-compatible dependencies.   Generally MSRV doesn't decrease over "
"versions, so minimal resolution will likely pick packages with compatible "
"rust-versions."
msgstr ""

#: src/3537-msrv-resolver.md:944
msgid "`cargo add` helps by selecting rust-version-compatible minimum bounds"
msgstr ""

#: src/3537-msrv-resolver.md:945
msgid ""
"This bypasses a lot of complexity either from exploding the number of states "
"we support or giving users control over the fallback by making the field an "
"array of strategies."
msgstr ""

#: src/3537-msrv-resolver.md:946
msgid ""
"Instead of `resolver = \"3\"`, we could just change the default for everyone"
msgstr ""

#: src/3537-msrv-resolver.md:947
msgid ""
"The number of maintainers verifying latest dependencies is likely relatively "
"low and they are more likely to be \"in the know\", making them less likely "
"to be negatively affected by this. Therefore, we could probably get away "
"with treating this as a minor incompatibility"
msgstr ""

#: src/3537-msrv-resolver.md:951
msgid ""
"Either way, the concern is to ensure that the change receives attention. We "
"wouldn't want this to be like sparse registries where a setting exists and "
"we change the default and people hardly notice (besides any improvements)"
msgstr ""

#: src/3537-msrv-resolver.md:953
msgid ""
"`cargo build` will treat incompatible MSRVs as a workspace-level lint, "
"rather than a package level lint, to avoid the complexity of mapping the "
"dependency to a workspace-member to select `[lint]` tables to respect and "
"then dealing with unifying conflicting levels in between `[lint]` tables "
"among members."
msgstr ""

#: src/3537-msrv-resolver.md:954
msgid ""
"`--ignore-rust-version` picks absolutely the latest dependencies to support "
"both users on latest rustc and users wanting \"unsupported\" dependencies, "
"at the cost of users not on the latest rustc but still wanting latest more "
"up-to-date dependencies than their MSRV allows"
msgstr ""

#: src/3537-msrv-resolver.md:955
msgid ""
"Compilation commands (e.g. `cargo check`) will take on two meanings for `--"
"ignore-rust-version`, (1) `allow` the workspace diagnostic and (2) resolve "
"changed dependencies to latest when syncing `Cargo.toml` to `Cargo.lock`."
msgstr ""

#: src/3537-msrv-resolver.md:956
msgid "This expansion of scope is for consistency"
msgstr ""

#: src/3537-msrv-resolver.md:957
msgid ""
"Being a flag to turn the `deny` into an `allow` is a high friction workflow "
"that we expect users to not be too negatively impacted by this expansion."
msgstr ""

#: src/3537-msrv-resolver.md:958
msgid ""
"With the resolver config and the configurable lint, we also expect the flag "
"on compilation commands to be diminished in value.  Maybe in the future we "
"could even deprecate it and/or hide it."
msgstr ""

#: src/3537-msrv-resolver.md:959
msgid ""
"`--update-rust-version` picks `rustc --version`\\-compatible dependencies so "
"users can easily walk the treadmill of updating their dependencies / MSRV , "
"no matter their `rustc` version."
msgstr ""

#: src/3537-msrv-resolver.md:960
msgid ""
"There is little reason to select an MSRV higher than their Rust toolchain"
msgstr ""

#: src/3537-msrv-resolver.md:961
msgid ""
"We should still be warning the user that new dependencies are available if "
"they upgrade their Rust toolchain"
msgstr ""

#: src/3537-msrv-resolver.md:962
msgid "This comes at the cost of inconsistency with `--ignore-rust-version`."
msgstr ""

#: src/3537-msrv-resolver.md:963
msgid ""
"Nightly `cargo publish` with `\"tbd-name-representing-currently-running-rust-"
"toolchain\"` fails because there isn't a good value to use and this gives us "
"flexibility to change it later (e.g. just leaving the `rust-version` as "
"unset)."
msgstr ""

#: src/3537-msrv-resolver.md:965
msgid ""
"Ensuring the registry Index has `rust-version` without affecting quality"
msgstr ""

#: src/3537-msrv-resolver.md:967
msgid ""
"The user experience for this is based on the extent and quality of the data. "
"Ensuring we have `package.rust-version` populated more often (while "
"maintaining quality of that data) is an important problem but does not have "
"to be solved to get value out of this RFC and can be handled separately."
msgstr ""

#: src/3537-msrv-resolver.md:972
msgid ""
"We chose an opt-in for populating `package.rust-version` based on `rustc --"
"version` (`\"tbd-name-representing-currently-running-rust-toolchain\"`). "
"This will encourage a baseline of quality as users are developing with that "
"version and `cargo publish` will do a verification step, by default. This "
"will help seed the Index with more `package.rust-version` data for the "
"resolver to work with. The downside is that the `package.rust-version` will "
"likely be higher than it absolutely needs. However, considering our "
"definition of \"support\" and that the user isn't bothering to set an MSRV "
"themself, aggressively updating is likely fine in this case, especially "
"since we'll let dependents override the build failure for MSRV-incompatible "
"packages."
msgstr ""

#: src/3537-msrv-resolver.md:979
msgid "Some alternative solutions include:"
msgstr ""

#: src/3537-msrv-resolver.md:981
msgid ""
"When missing, `cargo publish` could inject `package.rust-version` using the "
"version of rustc used during publish. **However**, this will err on the side "
"of a higher MSRV than necessary and the only way to work around it is to set "
"`CARGO_RESOLVER_PRECEDENCE=maximum` which will then lose all other "
"protections. As we said, this is likely fine but then there will be no way "
"to opt-out for the subset of maintainers who want to keep their support "
"definition vague. As things evolve, we could re-evaluate making `\"tbd-name-"
"representing-currently-running-rust-toolchain\"` the default."
msgstr ""

#: src/3537-msrv-resolver.md:988
msgid ""
"~~We could encourage people to set their MSRV by having `cargo new` default "
"`package.rust-version`.~~ **However**, if people aren't committed to "
"verifying that was implicitly set, it is likely to go stale and will claim "
"an MSRV much older than what is used in practice. If we had the hard-error "
"resolver mode and [clippy warning people when using API items stabilized "
"after their MSRV](https://github.com/rust-lang/rust-clippy/issues/6324), "
"this will at least annoy people into either being somewhat compatible or "
"removing the field."
msgstr ""

#: src/3537-msrv-resolver.md:995
msgid ""
"~~When missing, `cargo publish` could inject `package.rust-version` inferred "
"from `package.edition` and/or other `Cargo.toml` fields.~~ **However**, this "
"will err on the side of too low of an MSRV. These fields have an incomplete "
"picture. While this helps ensure there is more data for the MSRV-aware "
"resolver, future analysis wouldn't be able to distinguish between inferred "
"and explicit `package.rust-version`s. We'd also need an explicit opt-out for "
"those who intentionally don't want one set."
msgstr ""

#: src/3537-msrv-resolver.md:1003
msgid ""
"Alternatively, `cargo publish` / the registry could add new fields to the "
"Index to represent an inferred MSRV, the published version, etc so it can "
"inform our decisions without losing the intent of the publisher."
msgstr ""

#: src/3537-msrv-resolver.md:1007
msgid ""
"We could help people keep their MSRV up to date, by letting them specify a "
"policy (e.g. `rust-version-policy = \"stable - 2\"` or `rust-version-policy "
"= \"stable\"`); then, every time the user runs `cargo update`, we could "
"automatically update their `rust-version` field as well. This would also be "
"an alternative to `--update-rust-version` that can be further explored in "
"the future if desired. There are aspects of this that need to be worked out "
"before going down this route"
msgstr ""

#: src/3537-msrv-resolver.md:1013
msgid ""
"Without gating this behind a flag, this will push people away from bumping "
"their MSRV only on minor version bumps."
msgstr ""

#: src/3537-msrv-resolver.md:1014
msgid ""
"Tying this to `cargo update` encourages other side effects by default (`--"
"workspace` flag would be needed to do no other update) which pushes people "
"to a more casual approach to MSRV updating, even if we have a flag"
msgstr ""

#: src/3537-msrv-resolver.md:1015
msgid ""
"We need to figure out what policies are appropriate and what syntax to use "
"for them"
msgstr ""

#: src/3537-msrv-resolver.md:1016
msgid ""
"While a continuous sliding window (`N-M`) is most commonly used today, it is "
"unclear if that is the right policy to bake in compared to others like "
"periodic updates (`*/M` in cron syntax) to be helping the \"Extended MSRV\" "
"users along with everyone else."
msgstr ""

#: src/3537-msrv-resolver.md:1018
msgid ""
"Is `stable` clear enough to mean \"current version a time of `cargo update` "
"with ratcheting semantics\"?  What name can work best?"
msgstr ""

#: src/3537-msrv-resolver.md:1020
msgid "When there still isn't an MSRV set, the resolver could"
msgstr ""

#: src/3537-msrv-resolver.md:1021
msgid "Assume the MSRV of the next published package with an MSRV set"
msgstr ""

#: src/3537-msrv-resolver.md:1022
msgid ""
"Sort no-MSRV versions by minimal versions, the lower the version the more "
"likely it is to be compatible"
msgstr ""

#: src/3537-msrv-resolver.md:1023
msgid ""
"This runs into quality issues with version requirements that are likely too "
"low for what the package actually needs"
msgstr ""

#: src/3537-msrv-resolver.md:1024
msgid ""
"For dependencies that never set their MSRV, this effectively switches us "
"from maximal versions to minimal versions."
msgstr ""

#: src/3537-msrv-resolver.md:1026
msgid "Configuring the resolver mode on the command-line or `Cargo.toml`"
msgstr ""

#: src/3537-msrv-resolver.md:1028
msgid ""
"The Cargo team is very interested in [moving project-specific config to "
"manifests](https://github.com/rust-lang/cargo/issues/12738). However, there "
"is a lot more to define for us to get there.  Some routes that need further "
"exploration include:"
msgstr ""

#: src/3537-msrv-resolver.md:1030
msgid ""
"If its a CLI flag, then its transient, and its unclear which modes should be "
"transient now and in the future"
msgstr ""

#: src/3537-msrv-resolver.md:1031
msgid ""
"We could make it sticky by tracking this in `Cargo.lock` but that becomes "
"less obvious what resolver mode you are in and how to change"
msgstr ""

#: src/3537-msrv-resolver.md:1032
msgid ""
"We could put this in `Cargo.toml` but that implies it unconditionally "
"applies to everything"
msgstr ""

#: src/3537-msrv-resolver.md:1033
msgid ""
"But we want `cargo install` to use the latest dependencies so people get bug/"
"security fixes"
msgstr ""

#: src/3537-msrv-resolver.md:1034
msgid ""
"This gets in the way of \"Extended published MSRV w/ latest development "
"MSRV\" being able to change it in CI to verify MSRV and \"Extended MSRV\" "
"being able to change it in CI to verify latest dependencies"
msgstr ""

#: src/3537-msrv-resolver.md:1036
msgid ""
"By relying on config we can have a stabilized solution sooner and we can "
"work out more of the details as we better understand the relevant problems."
msgstr ""

#: src/3537-msrv-resolver.md:1038
msgid "Add `workspace.rust-version`"
msgstr ""

#: src/3537-msrv-resolver.md:1040
msgid ""
"Instead of using the lowest MSRV among workspace members, we could add "
"`workspace.rust-version`."
msgstr ""

#: src/3537-msrv-resolver.md:1042
msgid "This opens its own set of questions"
msgstr ""

#: src/3537-msrv-resolver.md:1043
msgid "Do packages implicitly inherit this?"
msgstr ""

#: src/3537-msrv-resolver.md:1044
msgid "What are the semantics if its unset?"
msgstr ""

#: src/3537-msrv-resolver.md:1045
msgid ""
"Would it be confusing to have this be set in mixed-MSRV workspaces?  Would "
"blocking it be incompatible with the semantics when unset?"
msgstr ""

#: src/3537-msrv-resolver.md:1046
msgid ""
"In mixed-MSRV workspaces, does it need to be the highest or lowest MSRV of "
"your packages?"
msgstr ""

#: src/3537-msrv-resolver.md:1047
msgid ""
"For the resolver, it would need to be the lowest but there might be other "
"use cases where it needs to be the highest"
msgstr ""

#: src/3537-msrv-resolver.md:1049
msgid ""
"The proposed solution does not block us from later going down this road but "
"allows us to move forward without having to figure out all of these details."
msgstr ""

